Here's the TikZ code that visualizes the N-extendibility strategy for a thermal noise channel:
```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=3mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta, shapes, decorations.markings, calc}
\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    >=Stealth,
    node distance = 12mm and 15mm,
    state/.style = {circle, draw, fill=blue!15, minimum size=8mm,
                    font=\small, label=center:$\rho$},
    amp/.style = {polygon, polygon sides=3, draw, fill=green!15,
                  minimum width=12mm, rotate=90, anchor=south},
    bs/.style = {rectangle, draw, fill=orange!15, minimum width=10mm,
                 minimum height=8mm, font=\small, label=center:BS},
    mode/.style = {circle, draw, fill=red!15, minimum size=6mm,
                  font=\tiny, inner sep=1pt},
    line/.style = {draw, ->, thick},
    every label/.style = {font=\small}
]
    % Initial state
    \node[state] (rho) {};

    % Amplifier
    \node[amp, right=of rho] (amp) {Amp};

    % Beam Splitter
    \node[bs, right=of amp] (bs) {};

    % Thermal noise channels
    \foreach \i in {1,2,3} {
        \coordinate (out\i) at ($(bs.east)+(\i*5mm, -\i*1.5mm)$);
        \node[mode] at (out\i) (m\i) {$\rho_{\i}$};
        \draw[line] (bs.east) -- (m\i);
    }

    % Vertical ellipsis for N modes
    \node at ($(bs.east)+(0,-12mm)$) {$\vdots$};
    \node[rotate=90, anchor=south] at ($(bs.east)+(10mm,0)$) {N modes};

    % Annotations
    \draw[line] (rho) -- (amp);
    \draw[line] (amp) -- (bs);

    % Thermal noise labels
    \foreach \i in {1,2,3} {
        \node[below=1mm of m\i] (n\i) {Thermal noise};
        \draw[line, gray!50, dashed] (m\i.south) -- (n\i.north);
    }
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```
This code produces a diagram showing:
1. An initial quantum state ρ in a blue circle
2. An amplifier (green triangle) labeled "Amp"
3. A beam splitter (orange rectangle) labeled "BS"
4. Three output modes (red circles) labeled ρ₁, ρ₂, ρ₃
5. Vertical ellipsis indicating N total modes
6. Dashed gray lines connecting each mode to thermal noise channels
7. Clear directional arrows showing the workflow
The diagram uses:
- Consistent color coding for different components
- Proper quantum notation for states
- Clear labeling of all elements
- Vertical ellipsis to denote N modes
- Dashed lines for thermal noise connections
- Professional arrow styles and spacing
The code maintains TikZ best practices with:
- Proper library imports
- Style definitions in the preamble
- Relative positioning using node distances
- Loop constructs for repeated elements
- Clean separation between graphics and text
You can adjust the number of displayed modes by modifying the foreach loop range and ellipsis positioning.

